04237nam a22006135i 9780271063867DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710638677 a10.1515/97802710638672doi  a(DE-B1597)584552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0060802bisacsh04a220.62231 aVaage, Leif E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBorderline Exegesis /cLeif E. Vaage. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignifying (on) Scriptures ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Text -- tIntroduction: Another Bible that Is Borderline -- t1 Into the Whirlwind: God's Answer to Job's Complaint -- t2 The Economy, Stupid! The Teaching of Jesus in the Gospel of Matthew -- tInterlude: Displaced Exegete: A Scriptural Biography -- t3 Such a Little Thing! The Tongue and Alternate Subjectivity in the Epistle of James -- t4 Interrupting Hope: The Book of Revelation -- tConclusion: After the Bible: Life's Largesse -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Borderline Exegesis, Leif Vaage presents an alternative approach to biblical interpretation, or exegesis-an approach that bends the boundaries of the traditional North American methodology to analyze the meaning of biblical texts for a wider audience. To accomplish this, Vaage engages in a practice he calls "borderline exegesis." Adapting anthropological notions of borderlands, borderline exegesis writes biblical scholarship peripherally, unearthing the Bible's textual and discursive borderlands and allowing biblical texts to be at play with the utopian imagination.The book's main chapters comprise four case studies that engage in a "divergent reading" of the book of Job, the Gospel of Matthew, the Epistle of James, and the book of Revelation. Informed by the author's time in war-torn Peru, these chapters take on themes that the poor and disenfranchised have historically claimed-themes of social justice, the legitimacy (or lack thereof) of prevailing social practices, and, most importantly, utopian demand for another possible world. The chapters are held together by the presentation of a greater theoretical framework that provides reflection on the exegetical practices within and confronts biblical scholars with important questions about the aims of the work they do. Taken as a whole, Borderline Exegesis seeks to disclose what the professional practice of textual interpretation might become if we refuse the conventional distances between academic practice and lived experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271063867423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271063867.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK